[1] Norovirus, healthcare facilities - Australia (NSW)
Date: Wed 21 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Orange.yourguide.com, Wed 21 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://orange.yourguide.com.au/detail.asp?class=news&subclass=local&categor
y=general%20news&story_id=322443&y=2004&m=7>

Australia: viral gastroenteritis affects Orange City region (NSW)
----------------------------------------------
A combination of gastroenteritis and flu-like symptoms have struck
several Orange residents causing them to seek medical attention.
Orange City General Practitioner Dr. Leonora Anderson said a
combination of poor hygiene and virus droplets had accounted for a
wide range of age groups being affected in the past 6 to 8 weeks. The
gastroenteritis virus has affected more than 400 people in the region
but has not reached epidemic proportions in Orange City. Dr. Ken
Hazelton said that he had not seen a rise in the number of patients
complaining of viral gastroenteritis. "I know Cowra and Gilgandra
have been badly affected, but Orange seems to have missed out," Dr.
Hazelton said.
Mid-Western Area Health infectious disease surveillance officer Gail
Osborne said this year [2004] was particularly bad. "We have recorded
more than 400 cases of norovirus infection across the Mid-Western
Area Health region, and these are only cases where people have had
testing done, there would be many more in the community," she said.
The virus is spread by coming into contact with an infected person,
and the symptoms are vomiting, diarrhea, fever, abdominal pain, and
headache. "The best way to avoid the virus is to continuously wash
hands, especially when preparing or eating food, and, after you have
used the toilet."
Institutions, such as nursing homes and childcare centers, are most
at risk. Trish Merchant, manager of Wontama Hostel, said the
residents were badly affected by the virus. "It was a particularly
virulent strain of norovirus this year [2004], but we confined the
residents to their rooms, focused on hygiene, and were able to
contain it fairly well." Snug as a Rug Childcare Center director
Olivia Picker said the center had a lot of children affected. "A lot
of our kids have been affected with vomiting, diarrhea and a high
fever."
[Byline: Yeena Kirkbright]
