[2] Norovirus, swimming area, National Park - USA (Oregon)
Date: Wed 21 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Oregononline.com, Wed 21 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.oregonlive.com/metroeast/oregonian/index.ssf?/base/metro_east_ne
ws/109041128534340.xml>

USA: Norovirus outbreak at Blue Lake Regional Park in Oregon
-----------------------------------------------
The swimming area at Blue Lake Regional Park will remain closed
through at least Sunday [25 Jul 2004], health officials said Tuesday
[20 Jul 2004], denying hundreds of swimmers a cooling dip as
temperatures soar into the 90s. The popular swimming beach was closed
Fri 23 Jul 2004 after 2 groups of swimmers reported bouts of diarrhea
and vomiting to Multnomah County health officials. By Sun 25 Jul
2004, more than 100 people, who had been swimming in the lake,
reported similar symptoms.
Tests on stool samples provided by victims revealed the presence of
noroviruses, said Dr. Gary Oxman, Multnomah County's health officer.
(Noroviruses include Norwalk virus and Norwalk-type viruses, which
gained notoriety for sickening cruise ship passengers).
Oxman said that human feces in the water, which is then ingested by
swimmers, is how most waterborne outbreaks occur. According to the
national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, noroviruses can
cause stomach pain, diarrhea, and vomiting that can last as long as
60 hours, after a 12-hour to 2-day incubation period.
Oxman said only a handful of people called health officials on Tues
20 Jul 2004 to say they got sick after swimming in the lake. The
outbreak has not diminished demand for picnic space at the park,
officials said. Boating, and other park activities, are not affected.
2 sporting events, planned for Sat 24 and Sun 25 Jul 2004, will drop
the swimming component.
The park, and its 64-acre lake, north of Fairview off Northeast 223rd
Avenue, attracts about 1400 people on warm summer weekends. Health
and park officials said they will meet again Monday [26 Jul 2004] and
will probably decide then when to reopen the lake to swimmers.
[Byline: Stuart Tomlinson]
